{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἀδάμ-ας</b>, αντος, ὁ, <br /> (δαμάω):—first in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus (in 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus only as _proper name_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], properly, <b>unconquerable:</b> <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> <i>substantive</i>, <b>adamant</b>, i. e. the hardest metal, probably <b>steel</b>, χλωρός, πολιός, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 231, “Th.” 161: _metaphorically_, ἀδάμαντος ἔχον κρατερόφρονα θυμόν “Op.” 147 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of anything <b>fixed, unalterable</b>, ἔπος ἐρέω ἀδάμαντι πελάσσας Oracle texts cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.141\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀδάμαντος δῆσεν ἅλοις fixed them with nails <b>of adamant</b>, i. e. inevitably, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.71, compare “APl.” 4.167 (Antip. Sid.); τὸν ἐν Ἅιδα κινήσαις ἀδάμαντα 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 2.34. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> <b>diamond</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Lapidibus” 19, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 8.18.6, “Peripl. M.Rubr.” 56; probably so meant in 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 59b, “Plt.” 303e, compare 1st c.AD: Plinius Rerum Naturalium Scriptor “Historia Naturalis” 37.55. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.3</b></Level3> <i>metaphorically</i>, ὁ πόνος ἀδ άμαντος, of love, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 245.13. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>adjective</i>, <b>unbreakable</b>, ἀνακτίτης[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Orphica “Lithica” 192.\">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G6134","accentedUnicode":"ἀδάμας","shortDef":"adamant","mediumDef":"adamant","stepGloss":"adamant","stepTransliteration":"adamas","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}